                <head>216. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On August 30, Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName> notified
                    President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> that Great Britain
                    would be sending to Canton Island two long-range aircraft which would “carry out
                    a photographic reconnaissance of certain British islands in the Central Pacific
                    which may be suitable as sites for testing thermo-nuclear weapons,” and asked
                    the President to inform <persName corresp="#p_SLL1">Lewis L. Strauss</persName>,
                    Chairman of the Atomic Energy Commission, and Admiral <persName
                        corresp="#p_RAAW1">Arthur W. Radford</persName>, Chairman of the Joint
                    Chiefs of Staff, of the purpose of these flights. In his reply on August 31, the
                    President assured the Prime Minister “that this government has no objection to
                    your carrying on the aerial explorations from Canton Island that you have
                    described.” (Eisenhower Library, Whitman File, International File)</p>
